SIMPLE: parting
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Parting
<hw>Par"ting</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧rt"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Part</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Serving to part;
dividing; separating.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Given when departing; <as>as, a <ex>parting</ex>
shot; a <ex>parting</ex> salute.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Give him that
<xex>parting</xex> kiss.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Departing.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Speed the <xex>parting</xex>
guest.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Admitting of being parted; partible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Parting fellow</b></col>, <cd>a partner.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Parting
pulley</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Pulley</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Parting
sand</b></col> <fld>(Founding)</fld>, <cd>dry, nonadhesive sand,
sprinkled upon the partings of a mold to facilitate the separation.</cd>
-- <col><b>Parting strip</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>in a sash
window, one of the thin strips of wood let into the pulley stile to keep
the sashes apart; also, the thin piece inserted in the window box to
separate the weights.</cd> -- <col><b>Parting tool</b></col>
<fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a thin tool, used in turning or planing, for
cutting a piece in two.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1047 --></p>

<p><ent>Parting</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Parting
<hw>Par"ting</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧rt"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of parting or dividing; the state of being parted;
division; separation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>parting</xex> of the
way.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ezek. xxi. 21.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A separation; a leave-taking.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And there were sudden <qex>partings</qex>, such as press⟦br⟧
The life from out young hearts.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A surface or line of separation where a division
occurs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>The surface of the sand of one
section of a mold where it meets that of another section.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The separation and determination
of alloys; esp., the separation, as by acids, of gold from silver in the
assay button.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A joint or fissure, as in a coal
seam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The breaking, as of a cable, by
violence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Lamellar separation in a
crystallized mineral, due to some other cause than cleavage, as to the
presence of twinning lamell⟦ae⟧.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Partisan</ent>⟦br⟧
